@Lucy Ferrinii~ I agree with you on a lot of this. 

Hmm, it's true that smoking could impact everyone. Anyone couId really get sick by smoking a lot.

 I also really like your catchy title!

@Molly McCafferty 
> “I notice from the data that there seems to be an effect on income whether you smoke or not.”
I see where you are coming from, but I have to disagree with you. I think this is an observational study, not a randomized and controlled experiment. Because of that, we cannot prove a cause-effect relationship here.

@Jade S 
I really like how you phrase it as “people with higher incomes tend to smoke less.” A lot of people might see this graph and think that being poor leads to smoking more, but we don’t know that from this observational study. No causal relationship can be assumed.
I also like your suggestion that we should lessen the wealth gap in this country.

@Lauren Iskander did you know that the average cost of cigarettes in NYC is a whopping $13???  At a pack per day, that is $4,745!!!  

In statistics, there can only be a cause-and-effect relationship if we perform an experiment.  We would need to randomly assign a large group of individuals to one of two groups: where all members of one group are assigned to smoke and all members of the other group are assigned to not to smoke.  We would collect income information from all members of each group for many years. Then we would compare the average income for each group. Given what we know about the harmfulness of smoking, such an experiment would be unethical. When an experiment cannot be conducted, we can use observational studies to learn about the relationship between variables like smoking and income.

The data represented in this graph comes from an observational study, so there is NO cause-and-effect, but rather an association.
